<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-608-862  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 608 862.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  Sept 4 1989 v8 n18 p100(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Pub. Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Letters. (letter to the editor)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kurtus, Ron.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT/><TEXT>LETTERSandM;The Philosophy of TQMandM;In reference to the July 24 article on total quality management (TQM) atNASA, TQM is more than &quot;doing it right the first time.&quot;andP;  It is continuallyimproving the quality of the product or service we deliver to our customers.andM;The philosophy of TQM is being advocated within the Defense Department, andone of the leaders in implementing TQM is the Space-Based Interceptor (SBI)program, which has been designated as the pilot TQM program within the SpaceDefense Initiative Organization.andM;SBI has tremendous software requirements, and the need for the highestquality product possible is paramount.andP;  Our contractors must develop softwarefor our system in a cost-effective manner, and our program office engineersmust perform their acquisition management in such a way as to ensure we getthe quality product we need for our mission.andM;Both of our contractors, Martin-Marietta Corp. and Rockwell InternationalCorp., have used TQM in their SBI programs.andM;The SBI Program Office also follows a strong TQM philosophy, ensuring ouracquisition process will result in the best product possible for thetaxpayers' money.andP;  They are the ultimate customer.andM;It is the attitude of working together to deliver quality goods that is anessential element in TQM.andM;But beyond that attitude is working to employ new methodologies for improvingthe quality of the software developed.andM;Lessons we learn in using TQM will be passed on to other programs, as aresult of our being a pilot program.andM;TQM works, and we are improving the way we do things every day.andP;  Ron KurtusTQM Manager Space-Based Interceptor Program Office Air Force Space DivisionLos Angeles Air Force Base, Calif.andO;</TEXT></DOC>